Consumer complaint narrative:
The Fair Credit Reporting Act ( 15 U.S. Code 1681 ) says ( 1 ) The banking system is dependent upon fair and accurate credit reporting. Inaccurate credit reports directly impair the efficiency of the banking system, and unfair credit reporting methods undermine the public confidence which is essential to the continued functioning of the banking system.

So whenever there is a violation under the FCRA, it impairs the efficiency of the banking system. This is a violation of my privacy with my consumer report, since I control what is listed and what is not. In the event that any accounts are reported without my written consent, that is considered identity theft.

This is a violation of both 15 U.S. Code 1681b ( 2 ) and 15 U.S. Code 1681c-2. This leads way to civil liability against the credit reporting agency for negligent and willful noncompliance under 15 U.S. Code 1681n, which allows for {$1000.00} per violation, for account listed without my expressed written consent.

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to formally request the blocking and deletion of all accounts associated with my personal information due to the recent data breach. 

Accounts in Question : XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX : : XXXX XXXX XXXX AAccccoouunntt NNuummbbeerr : : XXXX This request is made in accordance with several provisions of the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) : XXXX. XXXX XXXX XXXX ( a ) : This statute requires consumer reporting agencies to block information resulting from identity theft. I request that all accounts fraudulently opened in my name be blocked immediately. 

XXXX. XXXX XXXX XXXX : Under this section, I am entitled to dispute and request the deletion of any inaccurate or unverifiable information on my credit report. Please investigate and delete any such information linked to this breach. 

XXXX. XXXX XXXX XXXX ( b ) : This provision mandates that consumer reporting agencies maintain reasonable procedures to ensure the accuracy of information. Given the breach, I request a thorough review of my credit report to identify and rectify any inaccuracies. 

XXXX. XXXX XXXX XXXX ( a ) : I request access to my complete consumer report, as I have the right to understand what information is being reported and to identify potential inaccuracies resulting from this breach. 

XXXX. XXXX XXXX XXXX : As required by this statute, please ensure that any negative information resulting from the breach is not reported inappropriately. 

XXXX. XXXX XXXX XXXX : I reserve the right to seek damages for any violations of the FCRA resulting from this breach, should you fail to comply with my requests. 

Please confirm the receipt of this letter and provide written confirmation of the actions taken regarding my accounts. 

Additionally, I would appreciate an update on any measures you are implementing to protect my personal information. 

Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter. I look forward to your immediate response in 4 days!

Consumer complaint narrative:
" I am writing to formally file a complaint regarding unauthorized accounts that persist on my credit report despite my repeated efforts to have them removed. These accounts are causing significant damage to my financial reputation and overall well-being. It is evident that the inclusion of these fraudulent items violates 15 USC 1681b regarding permissible purposes, as the credit bureaus have no legitimate reason to report them without my explicit consent. Please refer to the attached file detailing these items I am disputing.

The Fair Credit Reporting Act ( 15 U.S. Code 1681 ) says ( 1 ) The banking system is dependent upon fair and accurate credit reporting. Inaccurate credit reports directly impair the efficiency of the banking system, and unfair credit reporting methods undermine the public confidence, which is essential to the continued functioning of the banking system. So whenever there is a violation under the FCRA, it impairs the efficiency of the banking system. This is a violation of my privacy with my consumer report, since I control what is listed and what is not. In the event that any accounts are reported without my written consent, that is considered identity theft. ''

I demand the late payment to be updated.

They are not in compliance with the following law. 15 USC 1666b and its requirements set the standards and the guidance for a creditor to treat a payment as late, yet they are reporting a payment as late and they did not comply with the law!

15 USC 1666b ( a ) Time to make payments A creditor may not treat a payment on a credit card account under an open end consumer credit plan as late for any purpose, unless the creditor has adopted reasonable procedures designed to ensure that each periodic statement including the information required by section 1637 ( b ) of this title is mailed or delivered to the consumer not later than 21 days before the payment due date.

EXPERIAN Never Sent the periodic statement along with the disclosures from section 1637 ( b ).

I have requested proof that this information was mailed or delivered 21 days before the payment due date and this information was requested in good faith
pursuant rule 1002 and It was never provided.

This is unfair, illegal, fraudulent, and not equitable to me as a consumer!

Update the late payments from my consumer reports

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to formally dispute the inaccurate information reflected on my credit report. The information appears to violate my rights under the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and should be removed or corrected promptly. The FCRA mandates that only accurate, complete, and verifiable information be included in credit reports ( 15 U.S.C. 1681e ( b ) ).

1. Incorrect Accounts Several accounts listed on my credit report appear to be inaccurate, incomplete, or outdated. Under FCRA Section 1681i ( a ) ( 1 ), I am entitled to dispute information that I believe to be inaccurate, and the credit reporting agency is required to investigate the disputed information within 30 days. I have reason to believe that the following accounts do not belong to me, contain incorrect data, or should no longer be listed due to age or resolution : XXXXXXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXXXXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXXXXXX As required under the FCRA, I request that these accounts be thoroughly investigated and either updated or removed from my credit report if found to be inaccurate.

2. Unwarranted Inquiries I also dispute the following credit inquiries listed on my report. Under FCRA Section 1681b ( c ), credit inquiries must be made with my permission or under circumstances where I have applied for credit. If these inquiries were not authorized by me or do not meet the requirements for a legitimate credit inquiry, they should be removed from my report : XXXX XXXX Please consider this my formal request for an investigation under the FCRA. If the items mentioned above are not removed or corrected, I will seek further action, including filing complaints with the CFPB and taking legal steps to enforce my rights under the law.

I am writing to address the ongoing inaccuracies on my credit report. Despite previous attempts to dispute the following items, they remain unresolved, significantly impacting my ability to obtain credit. I am entitled to monetary compensation under 15 U.S. Code 1681i ( 6 ), which requires consumer reporting agencies to notify consumers of the results of reinvestigations within five business days after completion. You failed to correct these errors indicates noncompliance with the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and Fair Debt Collection Practices Act ( FDCPA ).

Under the FCRA, if disputed items can not be verified, they must be removed from my report. As per 15 U.S. Code 1681n ( Civil Liability for Willful Noncompliance ) and 15 U.S. Code 1681o ( Civil Liability for Negligent Noncompliance ), your agency may be held liable for failing to comply with federal law. Additionally, 15 U.S. Code 1692k holds entities accountable for violations related to debt collection. Any continued failure to address these inaccuracies in a timely manner will result in further legal action.

Charge-Off Accounts listed below must be DELETED IMMEDIATELY! due to violations of FDCPA Section 807 ( False and Misleading Representations ) and These accounts are falsely reported as charge-offs.

Collection Accounts Collection accounts listed below is in violation of 15 U.S. Code 1681b ( Permissible Purposes of Consumer Reports ). These must be DELETED in my report immediately.

Unauthorized Inquiries listed below were made without my authorization, violating 15 U.S.C. 1681c ( 1 ) ( A ) ( B ) ( i ) ( 3 ). They must be deleted from my report.

I am formally exercising my rights under the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act ( FACTA ) to dispute and demand the immediate removal of the following inquiries from my credit file. These inquiries were either made without my full authorization, were not adequately explained to me at the time of application or have not been verified to my satisfaction. 

Inquiries to Be Deleted Immediately : XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXXXX/XX/XXXX Let me be clearaccording to Section 604 of the FCRA, you are prohibited from reporting any inquiry unless you can produce full documentation proving that I gave written authorization for each specific instance. Simply stating that the inquiry is permissible or initiated by the consumer is not adequate verification under federal law. 

I am requesting : Proof of permissible purpose for each inquiry listed above. 

A copy of the original signed authorization that explicitly allowed the pull of my credit report. 

Immediate deletion of any inquiry that can not be fully verified with supporting documentation. 

You have 30 days from receipt of this letter to complete your investigation and provide written confirmation of the outcome. If you can not comply, you are required by law to delete the disputed information from my credit file under FCRA guidelines. 

Failure to fully comply will result in the immediate filing of formal complaints with the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau ( CFPB ), the Federal Trade Commission ( FTC ), and the Attorney Generals Office in my state, as well as potential civil legal action for willful noncompliance. 

This letter serves as your final notice. I expect full compliance without delay.

Consumer complaint narrative: I am writing to express my concern regarding the disputed accounts on my credit report. Multiple times, I have raised the issue of inaccuracies in these accounts, and have consistently requested that they be thoroughly investigated. Despite my efforts, I have yet to receive any resolution or corrective action. These erroneous accounts are severely damaging my credit file and hindering my ability to live a normal life. The negative effects of these inaccuracies have caused immense hardships for me, and I am left with no choice but to plead for your assistance in rectifying this situation as soon as possible. I kindly request that you conduct a thorough investigation into the reporting of each of these disputed accounts. It is imperative that the necessary steps are taken to update and rectify my credit report without any further delay. With your help, I hope to restore the accuracy and integrity of my credit file so that I may regain control over my financial well-being. I sincerely urge you to give this matter your utmost attention and take swift action. Your cooperation and support in resolving this issue promptly would be greatly appreciated. Thank you in advance for your understanding and assistance.

Consumer complaint narrative:
" The Fair Credit Reporting Act ( 15 U.S. Code 1681 ) says ( 1 ) The banking system is dependent upon fair and accurate credit reporting. Inaccurate credit reports directly impair the efficiency of the banking system, and unfair credit reporting methods undermine the public confidence, which is essential to the continued functioning of the banking system.

So whenever there is a violation under the FCRA, it impairs the efficiency of the banking system. This is a violation of my privacy with my consumer report, since I control what is listed and what is not. In the event that any accounts are reported without my written consent, that is considered identity theft.

This is a violation of both 15 U.S. Code 1681b ( 2 ) and 15 U.S. Code 1681c-2. This leads way to civil liability against the credit reporting agency for negligent and willful noncompliance under 15 U.S. Code 1681n, which allows for {$1000.00} per violation, for each account listed without my expressed written consent.

I looked at my consumer reports and noticed accounts I never gave anyone permission to report. Consumer reporting agencies have assumed a vital role and have a responsibility to report consumer information to the best of their ability with maximum possible accuracy like the Fair Credit Reporting Act clearly states. I did not provide written consent to report them. ''

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to dispute fraudulent information on my credit report pursuant to 15 U.S.C. 1681c-2 and to request that this information be blocked. I have enclosed a copy of my police report and FTC identity theft report ( FTC Report Number : XXXX ) to support my identity theft claim.

Under 15 U.S.C. 1681c-2, when a consumer submits an identity theft report, credit reporting agencies must block any information identified by the consumer as resulting from identity theft within four business days.

The following information on my credit report is the result of identity theft and should be blocked : XXXX XXXX As required by 15 U.S.C. 1681c-2, please block this fraudulent information from my credit report immediately. This information should be blocked for one year, at which point I may request an extension of the block. During the block, you may not report any information that contains fraudulent data.

Several times I have contacted the credit bureau to report these fraudulent accounts on my report, and the bureau has not provided a solution to this issue. I am being seriously affected, as this situation prevents me from acquiring a new home for my children. These collections were already eliminated and not verified by other bureaus, so I do not understand why it is being claimed that these accounts are mine.

I have requested contracts from the company reporting these accounts, and for more than 60 days I have not received any response. Please help me by immediately deleting these accounts. I am attaching the FTC report, hoping that you will make a fair and appropriate decision in my case.
Company public response: Company has responded to the consumer and the CFPB and chooses not to provide a public response

Consumer complaint narrative: My account with XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX  XXXX was never late! I have had exceptional payment history witH XXXX XXXXXXXX and all payments were placed on Autopay. This late payment that is reporting is a result on a systematic error on their end processing my payment. This was clearly a billing error made my the company and is not a reflection of my payment experience which violates USC Code 1681eb. This error has caused severe hard to my reputation, my character, my mode of living and to my family! I demand the late payment reported in to be removed. b They are not in compliance with the following law. 15 USC 1666b and its requirements set the standards and the guidance for a creditor to treat a payment as late, yet they are reporting a payment as late and they did not comply with the law! 15 USC 1666b ( a ) Time to make payments A creditor may not treat a payment on a credit card account under an open end consumer credit plan as late for any purpose, unless the creditor has adopted reasonable procedures designed to ensure that each periodic statement including the information required by section 1637 ( b ) of this title is mailed or delivered to the consumer not later than 21 days before the payment due date. XXXX, XXXX, XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXXXXXX never sent the periodic statement along with the disclosures from section 1637 ( b ). I have requested proof that this information was mailed or delivered 21 days before the payment due date and this information was requested in good faith pursuant rule 1002 and It was never provided. This is unfair, illegal, fraudulent, and not equitable to me as a consumer! Delete the late payments from my consumer reports

Consumer complaint narrative: I am disputing inaccuracies on my credit report and requesting the immediate removal of specific accounts and items. These inaccuracies include unauthorized negative entries, incorrect addresses, and hard inquiries reported without my consent. These actions violate the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and the Fair and Accurate Credit Transactions Act ( FACTA ), particularly 15 U.S.C. 1681c-2, which requires consumer reporting agencies to block or delete information reported without written consent. You have failed to ensure maximum possible accuracy, as required under 15 U.S.C. 1681e ( b ). The reporting of unauthorized data also breaches 15 U.S.C. 1681b, which governs permissible purposes for obtaining and reporting consumer data. The inaccuracies have caused harm to my creditworthiness, and despite providing documentation, these errors remain uncorrected.

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to inform you that I am disputing the debt referenced above, which your company claims I owe. Under the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act, I am entitled to dispute the validity of this debt and request verification or validation.

Please be advised that : 1. I dispute the entire amount of the alleged debt.

2. I request that you provide validation of the debt, such as documentation available to verify that I agreed to pay the creditor, the current balance, a breakdown of charges, and an accounting of how the debt was reached.

3. You cease any debt collection efforts until this dispute is resolved and verified documents are provided to me.

4. I request my debt account not be reported to any credit agencies until you provide evidence validating the debt. 

As per my rights, I ask that you verify the debt and provide written proof that the debt belongs to me within 30 days. Also, please be aware that I request all future communications be in writing. 

If you are unable to verify this debt, I respectfully request that you confirm in writing that you are terminating collection efforts and will update all negative credit information relating to the matter. 

Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter. I look forward to your acknowledgment and kindly request a written response by [ specify a reasonable date, usually within 30-45 days ]. 

Sincerely, XXXX XXXX

Verify the balance for completeness and accuracy. 
Please confirm in writing the results of your investigation and send me an updated copy of my credit report. I am including a copy of my identification and proof of address to assist with your investigation. 

Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter. 
Sincerely, XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX

This letter serves as a formal follow-up to my previous correspondence regarding your agency 's ongoing refusal to comply with the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ), specifically in connection with my properly filed identity theft report submitted through IdentityTheft.gov. 

To date, your agency has not provided any satisfactory justification for rejecting this report, nor have you taken the necessary steps to investigate or remove the clearly fraudulent accounts listed below from my credit file. As reiterated in my prior letter, federal lawincluding FCRA Section 605B and Section 617requires you to accept valid identity theft reports from consumers, including those submitted through the Federal Trade Commissions IdentityTheft.gov platform. Nowhere does the law require that such reports originate solely from a law enforcement agency. 

Your continued rejection of my legally sufficient identity theft affidavit is not only unsupported by federal law but also constitutes willful noncompliance with the FCRA. This failure to act in accordance with clearly established legal procedures and CFPB guidance reflects blatant disregard for my rights as a consumer and victim of identity theft. 
Let me be clear : This is your final notice. You are in violation of federal law by continuing to report and verify accounts that were opened fraudulently and which I have already disputed with appropriate documentation. 

If I do not receive confirmation within 15 calendar days that these accounts heve been permanently removed and that my credit file has been updated to reflect the resolution of this matter, I will proceed to : 1.File formal complaints with the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau XXXX CFPB ), Federal Trade Commission XXXX FTC ), and my State Attorney General. 

2.Initiate legal action for your violations of FCRA Section 617 and for any damages sustained as a result of your unlawful reporting and failure to investigate. 

XXXX XXXX * * *

Consumer complaint narrative:
Full Name : XXXX XXXX Date of Birth : XXXX Last 4 digits of XXXX Agencies Involved : Transunion Creditor or Furnisher Name : XXXX XXXX  Account Number : XXXX Dear Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, I am writing to file a formal complaint pursuant to multiple violations of the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and potential violations of the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act ( FDCPA ) by credit reporting agencies and/or data furnishers. This complaint concerns the reinsertion of an account that was previously deleted from my credit report without the legally required prior written notification. 
Below are the specific legal violations involved : FCRA 611 ( a ) ( 5 ) ( B ) : Credit reporting agencies must notify the consumer in writing within five days of reinserting a previously deleted account. I did not receive any such notification, making this reinsertion unlawful.

FCRA 607 ( b ) : Requires credit bureaus to maintain reasonable procedures to ensure maximum possible accuracy of information. Allowing a deleted account to reappear without proper validation violates this section.

FCRA 623 ( a ) ( 1 ) ( A ) : Prohibits furnishers from reporting information they know or have reasonable cause to believe is inaccurate. Re-reporting a deleted account without new investigation is a breach of this statute.

FDCPA 807 ( 8 ) : Prohibits the use of deceptive or misleading practices in the collection of debts. Reinserting a deleted account may be considered a deceptive act.

FCRA 611 ( a ) ( 1 ) ( A ) : Grants consumers the right to dispute incomplete or inaccurate information. This account was previously disputed and removed, and its reappearance infringes on my rights. 

I respectfully request that the CFPB : - Thoroughly investigate the reinsertion of this account on my credit report. 
- Require the agencies to provide documented evidence of written notification within the legal timeframe. 
- Permanently delete the reinserted account due to FCRA violations. 
- Apply penalties or sanctions if a pattern of misconduct is found. 
- Provide me with a detailed report of your findings regarding this complaint. 


Thank you for your attention to this matter. I trust that the rights granted under federal law will be upheld. 

Sincerely, XXXX XXXX

My account was never late! I have had exceptional payment history all payments were placed on XXXX. This late payment that is reporting is a result on a systematic error on their end processing my payment. 


This was clearly a billing error made my the company and is not a reflection of my payment experience which violates USC Code 1681eb. This error has caused severe hard to my reputation, my character, my mode of living and to my family!

I demand the late payment to be updated.

They are not in compliance with the following law. 15 USC 1666b and its requirements set the standards and the guidance for a creditor to treat a payment as late, yet they are reporting a payment as late and they did not comply with the law!

15 USC 1666b ( a ) Time to make payments A creditor may not treat a payment on a credit card account under an open end consumer credit plan as late for any purpose, unless the creditor has adopted reasonable procedures designed to ensure that each periodic statement including the information required by section 1637 ( b ) of this title is mailed or delivered to the consumer not later than 21 days before the payment due date.

Never Sent the periodic statement along with the disclosures from section 1637 ( b ).

I have requested proof that this information was mailed or delivered 21 days before the payment due date and this information was requested in good faith pursuant rule 1002 and It was never provided. 


This is unfair, illegal, fraudulent, and not equitable to me as a consumer! 


Update the late payments from my consumer reports

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to formally request your assistance in resolving inaccuracies reported by all three major credit reporting agencies ( Equifax, Experian, and TransUnion ) on my credit reports. Despite my efforts to address these issues directly with the agencies, the discrepancies remain unresolved. 
The inaccuracies include : XXXX. Discrepancies on late payments : There are several instances where late payments are incorrectly reported. These errors are affecting my credit score and financial standing. 
XXXX. Incorrect information on original creditors : Some accounts list incorrect information regarding the original creditors, which is misleading and inaccurate. 
XXXX. XXXX balances and duplicate reporting : Some accounts are reported with XXXX balances and are duplicated as both a collection and a charge-off, which is misleading and negatively impacts my credit score. 
For example, on all my credit reports report : Account Name : XXXX  Account Number : XXXX Status : XXXX Potentially Negative Months Balance : {$0.00} Balance Updated : XX/XX/XXXX Additionally, the following account information is also inaccurate : Account Name : XXXX XXXX XXXX Account Number : XXXX Balance : {$4400.00} Balance Updated : XX/XX/XXXX Original Balance : {$4400.00} Status : 0 % paid off I have reached out to Equifax, Experian, and TransUnion to notify them of these inaccuracies and requested corrections. However, my attempts have not resulted in any meaningful resolution. 
Under the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ), I have the right to dispute incomplete or inaccurate information in my credit report. Specifically : Section 611 ( 15 U.S.C. 1681i ) : This section requires consumer reporting agencies to investigate disputes and correct or delete any information found to be inaccurate, incomplete, or unverifiable within 30 days. 
Section 623 ( 15 U.S.C. 1681s-2 ) : This section mandates that furnishers of information to consumer reporting agencies must not report information that they know or have reasonable cause to believe is inaccurate. They are also required to correct and update information.

Section 605 ( 15 U.S.C. 1681c ) : This section outlines the types of information that can not be included in consumer reports, such as outdated information.

Section 1666b ( 15 U.S.C. 1666b ) : This section specifies that a creditor may not treat a payment as late unless the periodic statement was mailed or delivered to the consumer at least 21 days before the payment due date. 
I kindly request the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau to investigate these matters and assist in ensuring that my credit reports accurately reflect my credit history. The continued presence of these inaccuracies is causing significant distress and financial hardship.
Company public response: Company has responded to the consumer and the CFPB and chooses not to provide a public response

Consumer complaint narrative: Fraudulent accounts were opened in my name without my consent as a result of being a victim of XXXX XXXX. These accounts include auto loans, credit cards, and collection accounts from various financial institutions. I was coerced into financial arrangements that I could not control, resulting in adverse entries on my credit report. Upon escaping the XXXX  situation, I discovered multiple unauthorized debts negatively impacting my credit. On [ specific date ], I contacted the credit bureaus to dispute these accounts and began the process of clearing my credit profile. I also worked with XXXX XXXX, a federally recognized organization assisting survivors of XXXX XXXX, to verify my victim status and obtain supporting documentation. Despite my efforts, the disputed accounts have not been fully removed or corrected. On I filed an identity theft report with the Federal Trade Commission ( FTC ) and submitted documentation to TransUnion requesting the removal of fraudulent accounts under 12 C.F.R. 1022.142. Consumer complaint narrative:
Consumer Reporting Agencies play a crucial role in gathering and assessing consumer credit information. However, they must exercise their responsibilities with fairness, impartiality, and respect for the consumers right to privacy. The banking system relies on accurate and fair credit reporting, and when these reporting methods are unfair, it undermines public trust, which is vital for the system 's stability. I never gave my explicit, written consent for these agencies to report my information, which is a violation of 15 U.S. Code 1681b ( 2 ). This violation has led to an alleged case of identity theft, breaching 15 U.S. Code 1681c-2. The accounts in question are not related to any transactions made by me.

The Fair Debt Collection Practices Act was created to ensure that laws and procedures are in place to protect consumers from abusive, deceptive, and unfair practices by debt collectors. In this case, the company has violated 15 U.S. Code 1692f, which prohibits debt collectors from using unfair or unconscionable means to collect a debt. Specifically, they can not collect any amounts that arent explicitly authorized by the agreement or allowed by law. Additionally, the company has violated 15 U.S. Code 1692e, which prohibits the use of false, deceptive, or misleading representations in debt collection efforts. This includes using deceptive methods to collect a debt or gather consumer information. Moreover, they are forbidden from contacting consumers at inconvenient times or places, or engaging in behavior that harasses or abuses consumers.

In this case, the company has harassed me by claiming I owe a debt that I do not recognize as my responsibility. They have also contacted me at inconvenient times and places, in violation of the law. 
I request that you promptly verify or remove the following account : XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX This collection account violates the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act ( 15 U.S.C. 1692g ) and the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( 15 U.S.C. 1681 ), as it has not been properly validated ; failure to remove it will result in legal action for non-compliance with federal law. - I have no recollection of this account. Please investigate and remove from my credit report.

I am requesting immediate corrective action to remove or amend the disputed accounts, as Experian 's inaction violates federal law and my rights as a consumer.

I contacted the merchant on XXXX to report the issue and requested either a refund or a cancellation of the purchase.

I have attempted to explain the situation to the collection agency, but collection activity has continued. I believe I should not be held responsible for this debt because the product was defective and my dispute was raised promptly after delivery.

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am reporting identity theft resulting in both a fraudulent account and multiple unauthorized hard inquiries on my credit reports. 

Fraudulent Account : A XXXX XXXX  credit card account was opened without my knowledge or consent and is being reported as charged off with a {$1300.00} balance and a {$1000.00} credit limit. The account was opened around XX/XX/XXXX, and last reported on XX/XX/XXXX. I did not open this account. It is currently appearing as a derogatory account on my XXXX  and TransUnion reports. 

Unauthorized Inquiries : On XX/XX/XXXX, multiple hard inquiries appeared on my credit reports from various lenders, including XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX, and others. I did not apply for credit with any of these companies. 

I filed an identity theft report with the FTC and a police report with the XXXX XXXX Police Department ( XXXX # XXXX ). I submitted disputes to both XXXX  and TransUnion with all supporting documentation, but the fraudulent account and unauthorized inquiries remain. 

This identity theft incident is damaging my credit standing and financial well-being. Under the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ), including Sections 605B and 611, the credit bureaus are required to block and remove fraudulent and inaccurate information. I am requesting the CFPBs help to ensure full compliance with federal law and the immediate removal of these fraudulent items from my credit reports.
Company public response: Company has responded to the consumer and the CFPB and chooses not to provide a public response

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to formally dispute and demand the immediate removal of an account that Experian has reinserted into my credit report without providing prior written notice, as required by the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ), XXXX XXXX. XXXX ( a ) ( XXXX ) ( B ) ( ii ). 
The following account, which was previously deleted, has now been reinserted : XXXX XXXX XXXX Balance : {$850.00} Violation of FCRA XXXX ( a ) ( XXXX ) ( B ) Under FCRA XXXX ( a ) ( XXXX ) ( B ), if a credit reporting agency reinserts previously deleted information, it must : XXXX. Certify the accuracy of the information with the furnisher, and XXXX. Provide written notice to the consumer within XXXX business days of the reinsertion. 
I received no such notice, making this reinsertion a direct violation of federal law. 
My Legal Rights and Demands Because Experian failed to follow the proper reinsertion procedures, I am demanding the following : Immediate and permanent deletion of this account from my credit report. 
A written explanation of why the account was reinserted without notice. 
A copy of the certification of accuracy that Experian claims to have received from the furnisher. 
If Experian Fails to Comply If this issue is not resolved within XXXX days, I will take the following actions : Submit a complaint to my states XXXX XXXX 
Pursue legal action under FCRA XXXX and XXXX, which provide for statutory damages, punitive damages, and attorneys fees for willful or negligent noncompliance. 
Final Notice This is a final demand for Experian to immediately delete the reinserted account and provide written confirmation. Failure to comply will result in regulatory escalation and legal action. 
Sincerely, XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX

Consumer complaint narrative:
I am writing to formally dispute an issue regarding a third party obtaining access to my student loan information and attempting to collect debt without my consent. I have recently become aware that [ NELNET a third party ] has been contacting me about my student loan and attempting to collect on behalf of [ the official loan servicer is The Department of Education, ] without proper authorization. 

I understand that the Federal Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act ( FERPA ) and the Privacy Act of 1974 protect my right to privacy concerning my educational and financial records. Under these laws, you are required to maintain confidentiality and are prohibited from releasing my loan information to any third party without my express written consent. The unauthorized disclosure of my loan information is, therefore, a direct violation of these privacy protections. Please provide my ( WET INK SIGNATURE ) written consent that show that I authorize a third party to have my personal information. 

Additionally, under the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act ( FDCPA ), a third-party collector must not engage in debt collection practices without having a proper legal basis for doing so. The FDCPA specifically prohibits third-party debt collectors from using false or misleading information, harassing debtors, or attempting to collect debts without proper documentation that proves they are legally entitled to collect on a loan. 

Furthermore, I have not given [ third-party NELNET ] written consent to access my loan information or engage in any collection activities on my behalf. Their actions are therefore in violation of the law and represent a breach of my rights as a borrower. Nelnet is a third-party service provider that works with the U.S. Department of Education . ( Nelnet handles a variety of tasks related to federal student loans, including loan servicing, payment processing, and assisting borrowers with managing their student loans. They serve as one of the companies that helps the Department of Education manage federal student loan accounts. ) I demand the following 1. An immediate investigation into how [ NELNET ] was able to access my student loan information and a complete explanation of how this breach of confidentiality occurred. 

2. A halt to any communication from NELNET regarding my student loan, including any debt collection attempts. 
3. Written confirmation that my student loan information will no longer be shared with any third party without my explicit consent. 

4. A formal apology from your office acknowledging the violation of my rights and a statement on how you will prevent future breaches of privacy. 
I request the cancellation of all student loans due to the presence of third-party involvement from Nelnet, which holds information that includes a wet ink signature. The existence of this signature raises concerns regarding the authenticity, accuracy, and legal standing of the loan agreements, potentially invalidating the current terms and conditions. Given these uncertainties, I believe that it is in the best interest of both borrowers and the financial institutions involved to cancel the loans and re-evaluate their legitimacy. This would ensure fairness, transparency, and accountability in the loan process, providing relief to borrowers who are currently burdened by potentially flawed agreements.l also I have attached information of them admitting that they are a third party Please confirm that these matters are being addressed within 30 days of the receipt of this letter. Failure to resolve this issue may result in further action, including but not limited to filing a formal complaint with the U.S. Department of Education, the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau ( CFPB ), and taking legal action as necessary. 

Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter. I look forward to your timely resolution.

This complaint involves Citibank regarding the misapplication of payments and incorrect late reporting on my account. This is a recurring issue, as I previously submitted complaint # XXXX regarding similar concerns. 

On XX/XX/XXXX, I agreed to a repayment plan with Citibank. 
On XX/XX/XXXX, I made two payments ( {$180.00} and {$92.00} ), which I understood would bring my account current for XXXX and XX/XX/XXXX based on information provided by a Citibank representative. Despite this, Citibank continues to report my account as late. On XX/XX/XXXX, I spoke with a representative ( ID : XXXX ) who stated that because I did not make an additional payment in XXXX, my account is considered past due. 

On XX/XX/XXXX I spoke with XXXX XXXX who indicated the account is not past due but the XXXX payment was not received. Even thought a payment was made on XX/XX/XXXX I would still need to make the payment that is due XX/XX/XXXX in spite the fact of XXXX confirming the account is current based on the repayment program. 

This contradicts the {$0.00} past due balance shown in my online Citibank account. Of which I have attached supporting evidence. Citibanks own correspondence states that payments can be made on or before the XXXX of the month. My XX/XX/XXXX, payment should have covered XX/XX/XXXX, as it was made within the allowable timeframe. Citibank appears to be applying payments strictly by chronological month rather than honoring their stated policy of allowing early payments. 

This situation has caused unnecessary damage to my credit report and financial standing, despite my adherence to the agreed-upon repayment plan. I request an immediate review of this issue and a formal response from Citibank through the CFPBs complaint resolution process.

Product: Credit reporting or other personal consumer reports
Consumer complaint narrative:
I am submitting this formal complaint against Equifax, TransUnion, and Experian for their repeated, systemic violations of my consumer rights. These credit reporting agencies have reported fraudulent accounts, unauthorized inquiries, and gross inaccuraciesincluding inconsistent open dates, mismatched account numbers, and contradictory payment historiesacross my credit file. Despite my dispute letters dated XX/XX/year>, none of the agencies have taken appropriate corrective action. I now seek immediate CFPB intervention to compel these agencies to expunge these fraudulent entries and to enforce robust compliance with every applicable law and industry standard, including Metro 2 reporting guidelines.

I. Background and Overview Without my knowledge or consent, the following four accounts have been reported on my credit file. Not only do they contain significant discrepancies, but they also flagrantly violate multiple provisions of the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and other consumer protection statutes : XXXX Account Number : XXXX Issues : Charged-off status ; inconsistent reporting of open dates and payment statuses across bureaus ; failure to provide required debt validation and notification. 
XXXX XXXX XXXX Account Number : XXXX Issues : Collection account with varying open dates and balance discrepancies ; improper handling of dispute and validation protocols. 
XXXX XXXX ( Entry One High Credit Amount Discrepancies ) Account Number : XXXX Issues : Reported with conflicting high credit limits and open dates that differ across credit reports, demonstrating an inability to maintain data accuracy. 
XXXX XXXX ( Entry Two Monthly Payment Discrepancies ) Account Number : XXXX Issues : Duplicate entry with monthly payment inconsistencies and differing open dates, further evidencing a breach of standard reporting practices. 
In addition, unauthorized credit inquiries from various entities ( XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX further compound these violations. 

Enclosed Exhibits 25 provide supporting evidence of these discrepancies and errors.

II. Detailed Account Discrepancies and Additional Violations Inconsistencies in Open Dates and Account Numbers : The reported open dates for the XXXX, XXXX XXXX XXXX, and XXXX XXXX accounts vary significantly between Equifax, TransUnion, and Experian. Such discrepancies not only violate the FCRAs mandate for maximum accuracy ( FCRA 607 ( b ) ; 15 U.S.C. 1681e ( b ) ) but also contravene Metro 2 compliance guidelines, which require uniformity and standardization in data reporting. 
The XXXX XXXX account appears twice with the same truncated account number ( XXXX ) but conflicting details regarding monthly payments and open dates. This dual reporting creates confusion and directly impacts my creditworthiness. 
Failure to Validate and Notify : Under 15 U.S.C. 1692g, creditors are required to send written notification of debt validation within five days. None of the disputed accounts were validated according to this statutory requirement.

The credit bureaus have not conducted proper investigations as mandated by FCRA 611 ( a ) ( 1 ) ( A ) and have failed to reinvestigate disputes per FCRA 611 ( a ) ( 6 ).

Data Inaccuracy and Metro 2 Noncompliance : The credit reporting agencies have failed to adhere to Metro 2 format standardsguidelines designed by the Consumer Data Industry Association for uniform data reportingwhich is evidenced by the significant discrepancies in account open dates, account numbers, and payment histories. 
Such noncompliance indicates systemic failures in maintaining data accuracy and proper dispute resolution protocols, further infringing upon my rights as a consumer. 
Unauthorized Credit Inquiries and Incorrect Personal Information : Multiple unauthorized credit inquiries have been recorded without my consent, violating both FCRA requirements and FTC guidelines under 15 U.S.C. 1681g ( e ). 
The inclusion of incorrect names and addresses on my file ( e.g., XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX  further constitutes a failure to ensure data integrity. 
III. Legal Violations and Applicable Statutory Provisions The actions and omissions in my credit reporting file violate numerous consumer protection laws, including but not limited to : Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) : 15 U.S.C. 1681e ( b ) ( Duty to provide accurate and complete information ) 15 U.S.C. 1681i ( Requirements for investigation of disputes ) 15 U.S.C. 1681n and 15 U.S.C. 1681o ( Civil liability for willful noncompliance and damages ) FCRA 607 ( b ) ( Mandate for maximum possible accuracy ) FCRA 611 ( a ) ( 1 ) ( A ) and 611 ( a ) ( 6 ) ( Timely investigation and reinvestigation of disputes ) Debt Collection Practices : 15 U.S.C. 1692g ( Requirement for prompt debt validation and notification ) Consumer Data Protection : Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act ( 15 U.S.C. 6801-6809 ) ( Obligation to safeguard consumer data ) Identity Theft Protections : Identity Theft and Assumption Deterrence Act ( 18 U.S.C. 1028 ) ( Criminalization of identity theft and fraudulent account creation ) State Law Violations : Illinois Law ( 720 ILCS 5/16-30 ) ( Enhanced protections and penalties for identity theft and misuse of personal information ) Metro 2 Reporting Guidelines : Although voluntary, these industry standards are designed to ensure data accuracy and consistency. The failure to comply with these guidelines further underscores the credit bureaus systemic negligence.

XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX, Tx XXXX XX/XX/XXXX Consumer Financial Protection Bureau ( CFPB ) XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX  XXXX, IA XXXX Subject : Formal Complaint Regarding Inaccurate Late Payment Reporting Dear CFPB Representative, I am writing to formally dispute an inaccurate late payment entry on my credit report, as allowed under the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( 15 U.S. Code 1681i ). This inaccurate reporting has negatively affected my credit profile, and I am requesting an immediate investigation into this matter. 
Details of the Disputed Late Payment : Creditor Name : XXXX / XXXX Account Number : # XXXX Date of Alleged Late Payment : XX/XX/XXXX and XX/XX/XXXX ( XXXX ) and XX/XX/XXXX and XX/XX/XXXX ( experian and XXXX XXXX I firmly believe this late payment is incorrect. Additionally, I am providing the following supporting evidence : Legal Basis for Dispute : Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) - 15 U.S. Code 1681i I am exercising my right under this section to dispute inaccurate information reported on my credit file. The reported late payment does not accurately reflect my payment history, and I am requesting a formal investigation and correction.

Truth in Lending Act ( TILA ) - 15 U.S. Code 1637 ( b ) Creditors must provide clear and accurate billing statements to consumers. If this late payment reporting does not align with the terms of my agreement, it constitutes an error that should be rectified immediately. 
Obligations of Information Furnishers - 15 U.S. Code 1681s-2 Creditors and furnishers must ensure that the information reported to credit bureaus is accurate. If the creditor can not substantiate the late payment with verifiable documentation, they must remove it from my credit file.

Requested Action : Conduct a thorough investigation into this dispute and provide a written response within 30 days as required by law.

If the late payment can not be verified, instruct the creditor to update my account status to " Paid As Agreed, Never Late. '' Notify the credit reporting agencies ( Experian, XXXX, and XXXX ) to reflect the corrected information on my credit report. 
Reference to PAANL ( Paid As Agreed Never Late ) : The terms of our agreement have always been adhered to, and the account in question should reflect a status of " Paid As Agreed Never Late '' based on the timely payments made. It is imperative that my credit report accurately represents my financial responsibility and commitment to meeting payment obligations. 

I hereby request that you provide documented proof supporting the claim of late payments on this account. This proof should include specific details such as dates, amounts, and any relevant communication indicating that the payments were indeed late. In the absence of valid proof, I expect the credit reporting to be rectified promptly. 

If, after a thorough investigation, you are unable to provide verifiable proof of late payments, I demand that the account be promptly updated to reflect its accurate status as " Paid As Agreed Never Late. '' Per the FCRA, I request that you conduct a timely investigation and provide a written response within 30 days from the receipt of this dispute letter. 

Failure to adhere to this timeline will be considered a violation of the FCRA. Appreciate your prompt attention to this matter and expect a resolution that aligns with the legal obligations outlined by the FCRA. Your cooperation is crucial in maintaining the accuracy and fairness of my credit report. 
Failure to properly investigate and correct this inaccurate information will result in further actions, including a potential escalation to legal authorities for non-compliance with federal consumer protection laws. 
I have enclosed copies of all supporting documents related to this dispute. Please acknowledge receipt of this complaint and provide a written update on the investigation 's progress within the legally mandated timeframe. 
Thank you for your time and immediate attention to this matter. I look forward to your prompt response. 
Sincerely, XXXX XXXX XXXX

The Fair Credit Reporting Act ( 15 U.S. Code 1681 ) says ( 1 ) The banking system is dependent upon fair and accurate credit reporting. Inaccurate credit reports directly impair the efficiency of the banking system, and unfair credit reporting methods undermine the public confidence which is essential to the continued functioning of the banking system.

So whenever there is a violation under the FCRA, it impairs the efficiency of the banking system. This is a violation of my privacy with my consumer report, since I control what is listed and what is not. In the event that any accounts are reported without my written consent, that is considered identity theft.

This is a violation of both 15 U.S. Code 1681b ( 2 ) and 15 U.S. Code 1681c-2. This leads way to civil liability against the credit reporting agency for negligent and willful noncompliance under 15 U.S. Code 1681n, which allows for {$1000.00} per violation, for account listed without my expressed written consent.

These inquiries lack my consent and as such, must be considered unlawful access. Furthermore, under FCRA 611 ( a ), I have the right to dispute inaccurate or unverifiable information and demand its removal. 

Please consider this a formal dispute and request for deletion of the above inquiries from my file. As mandated by the FCRA, you are required to investigate and respond within 30 days. Should these items remain without proper verification, they must be removed immediately.

Failure to comply may result in formal complaints with the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau ( CFPB ) and the Federal Trade Commission ( FTC ), along with pursuit of any legal remedies allowed under FCRA 616 and 617, which provide for damages in cases of willful or negligent noncompliance.
